WEBVTT

00:05.448 --> 00:09.140
In the morning I was shooting records in the house.

00:11.006 --> 00:13.213
And the big gun shot. to portray us. The big gun is 
shot, so I bide kindly back up in the house. The

00:20.430 --> 00:24.717
overseer asks me, what is that up that is thunder? I 
tell him, I don't know. I know what the amp is. And so

00:28.803 --> 00:36.535
he shot three times, and he commenced to shoot, 
until the pit commenced to rattle on the field. And

00:36.852 --> 00:46.306
he called me and told me to run down in the field and 
tell Peter to turn the people loose, that the

00:36.852 --> 00:46.306
Yankees come. And so I ran down in the field and 
hooped and hollered at him, Peter, and told him,

00:47.628 --> 00:58.184
Mr. Giggles, he'll turn the people loose because 
the Yankees come. The driver. And so he said that

01:00.067 --> 01:05.195
Wallace was lying. He said so. Like he said, so then 
the Yankee beat to the land and they drunk. You

01:10.653 --> 01:14.839
understand, they down south gettin' mighty poor. 
They used to drink coffee but now they drink dry.

01:17.744 --> 01:21.610
They say, let's raise the uniband, make the rebel 
understand. To leave our land for the sake of Uncle

01:21.630 --> 01:24.955
Sam. They down south gettin' mighty poor. Shut out 
the white cat and see the rebel run. I ain't gonna go

01:30.043 --> 01:34.089
with them two again. I'll get over all of them. Yes. 
And that, the people then show where they go then.

01:42.100 --> 01:49.815
They show where they go and they call we all up, you 
know, and give you all freedom. Because we are this

01:49.835 --> 01:52.320
much as free as them. Now you understand. But the 
Yankee thing must go back to the South there, help

01:54.524 --> 01:57.948
me. But they didn't. Of course, there was so much 
doubt and things in the way. They would have done

02:02.633 --> 02:04.556
more. But there's so much doubt in the way. It 
couldn't be called. The colored people sure went

02:08.921 --> 02:11.724
for it. And some white people sure went for it too. 
You understand? And the redder had them and had me.

02:21.715 --> 02:22.476
I'm satisfied so far. What the Lord has done for me, 
I come through to all who've been up and down

02:23.131 --> 02:30.956
through the militia. Well, tell me about how they 
went to Hawkinsville and drove the sword down on

02:30.976 --> 02:34.387
the ground. They told them, they know you.

02:40.681 --> 02:45.027
What do you remember about when slavery was over? 
You stayed at home when you stayed? I can't tell you

02:45.808 --> 02:47.551
about that. Well, hadn't you said you'd stay, 
okay? Go on, tell me about coming through here with

02:48.993 --> 02:51.397
cannons. Yes, yes. No, I'll tell you a mistake. Way 
back in slavery time, I would stand after the

02:53.560 --> 03:01.892
people were free. I would go out every day, right in 
town, to see the Yankees all going back home. I can

03:10.921 --> 03:27.975
really disagree that they have six and eight moons 
to count, going through, and boats on them,

03:10.921 --> 03:27.975
counting, counting, then they put the wagon, and 
have boats all on them wagon. What would it mean?

03:32.099 --> 03:32.820
Have a little mule. And one man, I ride him, ride the 
two mules. We always take a look at him. Have a look

03:38.168 --> 03:38.669
at him. All day long, I'd be crossing. I would just, 
well, and all the Yankees, I'd be like, dressed in

03:40.712 --> 03:45.279
blue clothes. I can remember, we'd go jump right 
here, and have a little pillow on the coat right

03:46.100 --> 03:57.117
there, in the background, and courses up there. I 
would go just as well, just to come down, and

03:57.517 --> 04:00.722
then... Black men have maybe, oh, I don't know how 
many black horses. Then they come along again with

04:06.536 --> 04:11.484
all these old green men on it. This is them cameras. 
And then they come back with horses, saw horses.

04:17.093 --> 04:18.576
All these have all gone to town. That way for two 
days, they've gone out to town for two days. And I

04:22.181 --> 04:25.647
remember, and the Yankees stopped here. And the 
maggots stopped right on the corner of the square.

04:30.176 --> 04:31.717
I was a good-sized boy then. And what they called 
freedom dealers, you know what I'm saying? And the

04:36.903 --> 04:41.769
prosecuting people, you know, what they do, you 
know, and all like that. And I regret hardly to call

04:42.049 --> 04:43.831
them. I've seen two men they had that were 
punishing for what they do. And I've seen them take

04:48.917 --> 04:50.959
them. That had a little big tent. We boys would go 
out and see him. And they'd take him, hang him up

04:55.485 --> 04:56.987
with a slum. And they'd let the tip, at that time, 
hang out so many men, they'd let him down. That's

05:03.018 --> 05:04.341
the punishment they got. We'd let the old man, he 
hadn't come, an old dead, his name was Yankee

05:05.783 --> 05:12.195
White. And the man, the judge's name,

05:18.462 --> 05:19.744
I forgot his name. But then I knew he looked like 
Yankee White. That's what he used to do when he was

05:22.567 --> 05:23.789
young. Well, then they come, and my old master, 
O'Connor McRae, he brought two of the horses for

05:23.809 --> 05:34.363
him. I rode the horse many times. One of them was a 
big horse they called Yankee Tom, a big, solid

05:36.766 --> 05:41.052
horse. And another big old horse was a saddle horse 
O'Connor McRae bought, and he was called Boston.

05:46.399 --> 05:48.081
He was a good, big, black horse. He took them all 
down to the farm. He took all of that. Good big boys,

05:52.784 --> 05:55.147
eh? Good big boys. And the Yankees would come, and 
at the fire, there'd be a whole troop of men come.

06:02.437 --> 06:04.921
They said they were Yankees. All walking. All 
walking. That crew of Yankees would go soon. Next

06:11.911 --> 06:16.717
time you see, there'd come a whole troop of 
Yankees. All riding horses. big guns hanging on

06:18.790 --> 06:22.155
there, all that stuff, you know. The oldest, 
tenderest man, all going home. And I said, I asked

06:26.461 --> 06:31.048
him, I said, I said, I said, Mama, where are they 
going? He said, they're all going home now. And old

06:33.211 --> 06:36.496
Colonel Crater, his old master, he was looking at 
it. He said, well, hey, all of you niggas is all free

06:36.516 --> 06:39.360
now. Yankees are all going home. I remember I got 
dishes for you. Right, right in town. So while we

06:45.729 --> 06:48.173
lived there, right where we knew The new post 
office. That's my old master's home. Up above the

06:54.462 --> 06:56.965
old post office. Well, that is his square. From 
that post office, clean down to the Citizen Bank.

07:03.714 --> 07:05.676
Oh, that is his whole square now. And clean over to 
the other part. Come out on up to the Church. That's

07:09.982 --> 07:12.124
my old master's place. I can remember he was a 
speculator. I can remember a good big boy then.

07:17.212 --> 07:20.875
They had a big old shed there. And they had cotton 
all in that shed. And we boys all got put on that shed

07:23.558 --> 07:27.181
every day. And they had wagons there. Every day 
he'd load up all them wagons and take all that

07:29.103 --> 07:33.106
cotton and go. Now you see, that was in slavery 
time. And he'd bring back a whole lot of colored

07:38.991 --> 07:42.134
people. They said he was a specklehead. And he'd 
sell them to all these people around this town.

07:48.541 --> 07:50.864
There's a lot of old people all dead now, but he 
brought them too. We'd all go up and bring them in.

07:55.450 --> 07:56.432
Oh, you look over there. My old, my old, my old papa 
was a wagoner. I used to go, he used to carry me with

08:01.339 --> 08:03.301
him all the time. Used to haul cotton, cat cotton, 
and jasmine to wire this bluff. And, and cat

08:10.992 --> 08:14.016
cotton, wire this, and this cat cotton, Over here, 
there's a place called...

08:20.669 --> 08:21.630
I forgot the place now. I can't come down there. I 
remember he used to be here. I was a good big boy at

08:25.554 --> 08:27.436
the time. And he had an auction. He had an auction. 
He had an old auction named Brandy. I thought, how

08:32.241 --> 08:34.103
come there's this wagon up? He'd get tired and sit 
down and build. Oh, yes, sir. Get on up. Get this

08:38.027 --> 08:38.568
one. Get on. And I'd ride old Brandy. Ride old 
Brandy and drive the rest of them. Right here, so I

08:44.135 --> 08:49.280
tried to get down and walk right on down. I'd be 
like, oh, Nick, I've been through a heap. A heap,

08:50.861 --> 08:52.443
all of that stuff. That didn't save a time. That 
didn't save a time. And I remember, I can tell you

08:55.706 --> 08:58.128
what saved a time. Right down, I can tell you this, 
if I can. Right down close to Mr. Nicky Mays' place,

09:04.754 --> 09:10.379
there was no jailhouse on. Old, long jailhouse. 
Over all jailhouses now. That's the only, that's

09:16.018 --> 09:23.390
the only, that's the only, and there was no, there 
was no, some kind of a courthouse. I rejected. And

09:24.592 --> 09:27.838
they used to put prisoners in that jailhouse. And 
me, me, and another young white fellow was raised

09:27.858 --> 09:33.928
in there, and call him a cray and hand him on. And we 
used to go home, the people that owned some things,

09:34.709 --> 09:39.437
we used to go home and steal. braid the stuff and 
focus with them little bars to the prisoners with

