11:53.399 --> 11:59.088
You told me a story or two about yourself and about 
your father as we came along. What was it? Well,

12:00.289 --> 12:05.457
just mention it so I know what you're talking 
about, and I can start it over with you and I'll read

12:00.289 --> 12:05.457
it. Well, was your father a songster like you? 
Nothing more than hymns, hymns. He was a regular

12:12.559 --> 12:14.182
church man. Well, what kind of songs did you sing 
when you were young? Well, I didn't just holler

12:18.129 --> 12:25.042
reels, just fiddle reels, you know, all the time, 
my singing. Were you a fiddler yourself? No, sir,

12:26.444 --> 12:28.648
no, sir. I couldn't make no music at all. Well, you 
could make music with your mouth. Oh, yes, I could

12:34.384 --> 12:35.785
do that. I sure would do that. Everywhere you'd 
hear me, you'd hear me singing a song, a reel. And

12:42.432 --> 12:44.854
out in the field, what'd you do when you were 
working? That's what I'd do, hollering, singing

12:44.974 --> 12:47.396
reels. And what was it you sang about the cotton? 
About Little Joe? Yeah. Little Joe. My son told me

12:56.265 --> 12:58.487
to pick a little cotton. The boy said, done for the 
seeds all rotted. Well, I said it just like you did

13:01.681 --> 13:04.244
to me in the car. I said it louder. My son told me to 
pick a little sun before he set down. Seat's all

13:11.172 --> 13:12.393
rotten. Get out of the way, old man. Tucker comes 
too late to kick through a slipper. I don't believe

13:18.300 --> 13:20.722
I heard you sing it. Well, how did you tell me you 
used to call your sweetheart out at night? Let me

13:24.767 --> 13:25.267
see. I nearly forgot what I was supposed to holler. 
What's all the hollering for? In hollering. They

13:30.487 --> 13:33.570
tell me one word every so often, what they're 
talking about. They said you didn't have any

13:33.590 --> 13:35.913
starch or salt. Yes. No salt. Louder. Sing it 
louder. No salt. No starch. Nobody to wash my

13:48.585 --> 13:53.270
clothes. Nobody to wash my clothes. I hate to say 
it, but my voice, it broke. Well, didn't you say you

14:00.895 --> 14:04.160
used to sing that in the field, too? Yeah, I sang 
that in the field, too. Yes. Would your sweetheart

14:07.525 --> 14:09.909
be out there in the field? No, she'd be joining. 
Joining fields, you know. Uh-huh. Well, what were

14:16.379 --> 14:19.984
some of the other old field hollers that you used to 
have? When you, I'm going home, I'm going home,

14:21.955 --> 14:34.106
I'm going home. I was one of them. Well, when you 
wanted to, when you wanted to summon a boy from

14:37.409 --> 14:45.217
across the creek, way far off, how would you, how 
would you notify? I just hollered, I hollered, you

14:45.237 --> 14:49.040
hear me holler, and he'd answer me way, way on. 
Well, what was the holler? That same thing I'll

14:51.638 --> 14:53.360
sing. No snow. No sky. Nobody to wash my clothes. 
Nobody to wash my clothes. The same old horror. And

15:08.335 --> 15:12.279
he danced way out of his field. What'd he say? 
Ma'am? What would he say? Well, he'd say the same

15:15.863 --> 15:17.805
thing. And how would he sing it? Sing it like he did. 
No sun, no stars. Nobody to wash my clothes. Nobody

15:32.496 --> 15:36.301
to wash my clothes. And if he took a notion, then 
he'd say, I'm going home. I'm going home. I'm going

15:48.476 --> 15:48.996
home. I know that he'd come as soon as he got supper. 
It's a white folk kitchen. I'm looking for him.

15:56.968 --> 16:03.040
Now, you told me about the man that you worked for 
for 10 or 12 years, Mr. Norwood. And you said he's

16:03.301 --> 16:05.665
the meanest man in the country. Well, they said so. 
Them Norwoods worked for the meanest people in the

16:07.389 --> 16:10.836
world around them. Well, how did it treat you? It 
treated me all right. The nine one of them never did

16:15.833 --> 16:19.579
cuss at me the whole 12 years. I didn't care what I 
went to them for, I got it. Bowels of flour, middles

16:23.265 --> 16:27.913
of meat, chags of molasses, money any time. Now 
that Judge Noah, as the oldest boy, if his store

16:29.159 --> 16:38.348
would be full of hands, you know, he was more than 
old to know what he was doing. I'd just tell him,

16:39.009 --> 16:41.271
give me a pencil and a piece of paper. He'd hand it to 
me, and I'd write it on there and tell him, I want a $5

16:41.631 --> 16:45.235
piece of it. I'd hand it to him, go on by my business. 
First thing you know, he'd come on by me, text me,

16:47.978 --> 16:50.900
and give it to me. He'd do me that way just to show me, 
just to show me that I'm a leader. What was it the old

16:57.593 --> 17:01.499
merchant, what was it the old merchant told you? 
You told the old merchant down here, Mr.

17:01.519 --> 17:06.065
Mooringford. Me and him was talking down one day 
and wasn't nobody in there but me. I say exactly

17:11.913 --> 17:14.197
what you said now. Yes, but wasn't nobody in there 
but me and him and his son and his son's daughter.

17:20.586 --> 17:22.268
And I said, Mr. Corrigan, I forgot exactly how old I 
was, but anyhow, I said, I'm 61 or two years old, and

17:22.720 --> 17:31.952
I never had no trouble in my life. I said, I never 
asked the noise for nickel, but they didn't give it

17:32.593 --> 17:38.020
to me, in my life. And that one of them never 
accosted me. And said, I ain't never been

17:40.843 --> 17:51.377
summoned, and ain't never been arrested, and 
ain't never been to the jailhouse but twice in my

17:40.843 --> 17:51.377
life, and ain't been to the courthouse but twice. 
He looked at me and cooked. He said, well, Bob, I'm

17:54.337 --> 17:55.980
down. That ain't too much for a nigga to say. He 
said, ain't no white man can say any better than

17:58.144 --> 18:01.890
that. He said, ain't. I said, well, I'm telling you 
the truth. I said, you can ask these people all

18:04.294 --> 18:11.847
around the school that know me, and they'll tell 
you I ain't never been in no trouble since I've been

18:04.294 --> 18:11.847
there. Well, you said you hadn't been to the 
jailhouse before. Did they put you in jail or what?

18:17.553 --> 18:19.095
No, I just went by there. Went by the jail? Down the 
street, yes. Well, when you had friends in jail,

18:21.878 --> 18:24.561
didn't you go to see them? I didn't go to see them 
because I always said, practice makes perfect. I

18:29.926 --> 18:32.569
cried, I said so, and I just wouldn't go to see them. 
I said, no, I ain't going to see them. I said,

18:34.671 --> 18:36.353
practice makes perfect. I ain't going there. The 
Lord knows I'm telling you the truth, what I said.

18:42.320 --> 18:46.045
